//! `baton-do` — multiplexed iRODS operations dispatcher.
//!
//! NDJSON in/out: each input line is a [`BatonDoEnvelope`] carrying an
//! operation discriminator, a per-operation target, and an optional
//! `arguments` block. Each output line is the same envelope plus
//! exactly one of `result` (on success) or `error` (in-band annotation
//! on per-input failure). Operation routing lives in
//! [`baton_rs::operations::baton_do::dispatch_one`]; this binary owns
//! IO, clap argument parsing, the reconnect watchdog, and the exit
//! code policy.
//!
//! Per-input failures are annotated and the stream continues. Parse
//! failures emit a stand-alone `{"error": {...}}` line and the stream
//! continues — see issue #37 for the documented divergence from
//! upstream baton-do's parse-error wire shape. Connection-level
//! failures are fail-fast.
//!
//! **Envelope round-trip fidelity** — top-level fields baton-rs doesn't
//! model are captured on deserialise (via
//! [`BatonDoEnvelope.extra`]) and echoed verbatim on the output
//! envelope. This matches upstream baton's "modify input JSON in
//! place, write it back" pattern (`baton/src/operations.c:130-150`)
//! and is load-bearing for downstream consumers that add their own
//! correlation metadata — most notably extendo's top-level `"ID"`
//! request-response correlation field
//! (`extendo/client.go:97-100, 382-396`). Removing the round-trip
//! would silently break extendo's response routing. See the
//! "Cross-cutting conventions" block in `SESSIONS.md`.

